The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, in particular, by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, prevents accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C which is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Brand Management Technology and Research and Development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan's four-area Safety Shield.
This robot intends to strengthen the collision prevention capacity of the vehicles of the brand.
During their flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that closely resembles Nissan's Safety Shield.
But the most important thing is the bee's compound eyes, able to see with an angle of over 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor which immediately results in the prevention of collision.
"The moment you detect an obstacle, the small robot will imitate a bee's movements and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at a right or higher angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
Otherwise, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and principal engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted up or down, or diagonally; it can only be moved in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It does not require saving information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can function continuously with just a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we're not talking about memory gigs, not even megas."
This is the first step in developing new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that Nissan predicts will be introduced into standard cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ions.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles along the way.
