Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refound the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the common project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, following the example of his colleagues and friends, he is the third to vote on a draft for a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of the voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results referring to 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were invalid and 0.7% were blank votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the polling stations and a recount by a non-governmental organisation had announced a broad victory for the "yes", estimating it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on Sunday to Monday night.
The "Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly," he had assured, congratulating Ecuadorians who head the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will take place in full calm, according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text of 444 points that consolidated the " new socialism " defended by the president.
The draft Constitution implies an increase in the State ' s power over the economy, reserving for it the " development planning " of a country that lives essentially thanks to the extraction of oil by foreign companies and thanks to foreign exchange sent by their émigrés.
Carried by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants reinforced powers to the head of State, who will be able to make up to two consecutive terms of four years each and will have the possibility to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa already announced that he would use this power and intend a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the president began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for the interdiction of the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American drug operations.
All 19 abducted persons have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released Monday afternoon.
By morning, they had been released by the Egyptian special forces in Chad.
They all looked good upon arrival at 15H30 aboard a special aircraft to the Al Maza military base adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical testing, so they have not been able to speak to the press.
"They are in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana declared at the airport.
On 19 September, these hostages fell into the hands of 35 unknown hijackers while enjoying a safari on SUVs in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, in the confines of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since passed from one pike to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian- and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, in charge of organizing the safari.
An Egyptian security officer indicated that 30 members of the special forces, transported aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
"An exchange of fire took place, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others have fled," said this responsible who kept the anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lighting" unit were sent to Sudan, where they had the support of German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men in the secret services, the special forces," he said without going into details.
He also denied payment of a ransom.
On the eve, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an SUV aboard which the kidnappers were present, of which six were killed, including the Chadian chief and two were arrested.
He also claimed that they were related to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan-Unit Liberation Movement (SLA-U), an allegation immediately denied by this group.
