European Union doubles its trade with India
As the European Union and India are mutually trading partners, this issue, in addition to the other largely global problems, dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A French-Indian summit will also be held today to deal mainly with cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a great democratic developing power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs but member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator as to whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue was not addressed at the ninth summit which began yesterday in Marseilles.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, EU President-in-Office, José Manuel Barroso, President of the Commission and Javier Solana, the main representative of foreign policy, received Manmohan Singh, Prime Minister of India, with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, i.e. increase their trade to more than one hundred billion euros.
Given that the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not an overly ambitious target.
They have thus legally harmonised the 26 existing bilateral civil aviation conventions with India, so that air transport will also be able to fly in the future.
India until the end of 2009 wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union.
Sarkozy promised to speed up negotiations.
The objective is balance, because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only ranked ninth among the Union's trading partners.
