Found Steve Fossett's plane the missing millionaire a year ago
The remains of Steve Fossett's plane, the millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, have been found.
The debris has been found on a highlands at 3000 meters altitude, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, in the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
Wood County Commissioner John Anderson has dispelled the remaining doubts: "The plane has been located, we have sent a squadron, and now we have the confirmation that it is that which Steve Fossett was flying over on the day of his disappearance" he said at a print conference.
The Commissioner has specified that no human remains have been found either on the plane or in the vicinity.
The 63-year-old millionaire was given up for death in February.
The American office for transport safety (Ntsb) has made it known that a few hours after the sighting of the remains, a squadron of researchers has been sent that has identified the apparatus: it is typical of Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, always in California, not far from the end of Nevada, some of Fossett's personal remains have been found by a couple near his Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents named Fossett, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett's search had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of firsts.
By 2002, at the sixth attempt, he had become the first Man to complete the turn of the world into a hot air balloon: two lonely weeks of flight.
Three years later he had made the turn of the world by plane and without stopovers.
Among his records, also that for having flown at 15,445 meters in height, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
